<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,1085,1685]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,356,1121,1146]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">DIAGNOSIS</emphasis>
: Based on historical description and illustrations (Raušer 1968), males and females are macropterous. The male epiproct (
<figureCitation box="[534,614,1157,1181]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–75" captionStartId="61.[151,263,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[163,1436,214,962]" captionTargetId="figure-70@61.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 72–75. Mesocapnia silvatica. 72: Male terminalia, dorsal; 73: Male terminalia, lateral; 74: Female terminalia, ventral; 75: Historical records map with range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
) is shorter than that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zwick" authorityYear="1973" box="[871,986,1157,1181]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Mesocapnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="altaica">
<emphasis box="[871,986,1157,1181]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">M. altaica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1000,1077,1157,1181]" captionStart="FIGURES 67–71" captionStartId="60.[151,263,1978,2001]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-80@60.[151,1436,1199,1968]" captionTargetPageId="60" captionText="FIGURES 67–71. Mesocapnia altaica.67: Habitus (preserved); 68: Male terminalia; 69: Female terminalia; 70: Nymph habitus; 71: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig.68</figureCitation>
), extending only halfway across tergite 9. The dorsal profile of the epiproct is sinuate with a slight constriction near the midlength (
<figureCitation box="[1257,1338,1193,1217]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–75" captionStartId="61.[151,263,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[163,1436,214,962]" captionTargetId="figure-70@61.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 72–75. Mesocapnia silvatica. 72: Male terminalia, dorsal; 73: Male terminalia, lateral; 74: Female terminalia, ventral; 75: Historical records map with range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 72</figureCitation>
) and the lateral profile is relatively uniform in width with an abruptly narrowing and upturned apex (
<figureCitation box="[1178,1263,1229,1253]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–75" captionStartId="61.[151,263,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[163,1436,214,962]" captionTargetId="figure-70@61.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 72–75. Mesocapnia silvatica. 72: Male terminalia, dorsal; 73: Male terminalia, lateral; 74: Female terminalia, ventral; 75: Historical records map with range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
). At the tip, the epiproct gradually tapers, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zwick" authorityYear="1973" box="[580,698,1265,1289]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Mesocapnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="altaica">
<emphasis box="[580,698,1265,1289]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">M. altaica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the tapering is more abrupt. Raušer (1968) describes the overall shape from the lateral view as that of a snipe (bird) head that is craned forward (
<figureCitation box="[1076,1162,1301,1325]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–75" captionStartId="61.[151,263,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[163,1436,214,962]" captionTargetId="figure-70@61.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 72–75. Mesocapnia silvatica. 72: Male terminalia, dorsal; 73: Male terminalia, lateral; 74: Female terminalia, ventral; 75: Historical records map with range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 73</figureCitation>
). The female subgenital plate is broadly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[451,536,1337,1361]" captionStart="FIGURES 72–75" captionStartId="61.[151,263,983,1006]" captionTargetBox="[163,1436,214,962]" captionTargetId="figure-70@61.[151,1436,193,962]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 72–75. Mesocapnia silvatica. 72: Male terminalia, dorsal; 73: Male terminalia, lateral; 74: Female terminalia, ventral; 75: Historical records map with range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 74</figureCitation>
) similar to that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klapalek" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[761,908,1337,1361]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Mesocapnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variabilis">
<emphasis box="[761,908,1337,1361]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">M. variabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[927,1012,1337,1361]" captionStart="FIGURES 76–80" captionStartId="61.[151,264,1875,1898]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,1085,1844]" captionTargetId="figure-74@61.[151,1436,1085,1854]" captionTargetPageId="61" captionText="FIGURES 76–80. Mesocapnia variabilis. 76: Habitus (preserved); 77: Male terminalia, dorsal; 78: Male terminalia, lateral; 79: Female terminalia, ventral; 80: Predicted ENM map with documented occurrences and range estimate." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
) and the two species are difficult to separate as females although they can be readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Zwick" authorityYear="1973" box="[926,1042,1373,1397]" class="Insecta" family="Capniidae" genus="Mesocapnia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="altaica">
<emphasis box="[926,1042,1373,1397]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">M. altaica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which has a more triangular plate. The nymphs of this species are unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
